04688nam a22005415i 9780822386087DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20052004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223860877 a10.1515/97808223860872doi  a(DE-B1597)553989  a(OCoLC)841913709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aE183.8.V5J33 2004 7aHIS0270702bisacsh04a327.730597/09/0451 aJacobs, Seth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerica's Miracle Man in Vietnam :bNgo Dinh Diem, Religion, Race, and U.S. Intervention in Southeast Asia /cSeth Jacobs; Emily S. Rosenberg, Gilbert M. Joseph. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2005] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b28 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 ''Colonialism, Communism, or Catholicism?'': Mr. Diem Goes to Washington -- t2 ''Our System Demands the Supreme Being'': America's Third Great Awakening -- t3 ''These People Aren't Complicated'': America's ''Asia'' at Midcentury -- t4 ''Christ Crucified in Indo- China'': Tom Dooley and the North Vietnamese Refugees -- t5 ''The Sects and the Gangs Mean to Get Rid of the Saint'': ''Lightning Joe'' Collins and the Battle for Saigon -- t6 ''This God-Fearing Anti-Communist'': The Vietnam Lobby and the Selling of Ngo Dinh Diem -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerica's Miracle Man in Vietnam rethinks the motivations behind one of the most ruinous foreign-policy decisions of the postwar era: America's commitment to preserve an independent South Vietnam under the premiership of Ngo Dinh Diem. The so-called Diem experiment is usually ascribed to U.S. anticommunism and an absence of other candidates for South Vietnam's highest office. Challenging those explanations, Seth Jacobs utilizes religion and race as categories of analysis to argue that the alliance with Diem cannot be understood apart from America's mid-century religious revival and policymakers' perceptions of Asians. Jacobs contends that Diem's Catholicism and the extent to which he violated American notions of "Oriental" passivity and moral laxity made him a more attractive ally to Washington than many non-Christian South Vietnamese with greater administrative experience and popular support.A diplomatic and cultural history, America's Miracle Man in Vietnam draws on government archives, presidential libraries, private papers, novels, newspapers, magazines, movies, and television and radio broadcasts. Jacobs shows in detail how, in the 1950s, U.S. policymakers conceived of Cold War anticommunism as a crusade in which Americans needed to combine with fellow Judeo-Christians against an adversary dangerous as much for its atheism as for its military might. He describes how racist assumptions that Asians were culturally unready for democratic self-government predisposed Americans to excuse Diem's dictatorship as necessary in "the Orient." By focusing attention on the role of American religious and racial ideologies, Jacobs makes a crucial contribution to our understanding of the disastrous commitment of the United States to "sink or swim with Ngo Dinh Diem."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Military / Vietnam War.2bisacsh1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822386087423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822386087.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles